'''Akureyri Golf Club''' is located in [[Akureyri]], Iceland, at ''Jaðarsvöllur'',<ref name=visitakureyri.is>{{cite web|title=Golf Course Jadarsvollur|url=http://www.visitakureyri.is/en/things-to-do/activities/akureyri-golf-club|website=visitakureyri.is|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref> it was named "the most northerly 18-hole golf course" according to the [[Royal and Ancient Golf Club of St. Andrews]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arcticopen.is|title=The Arctic Open|publisher=arcticopen.is|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-travel-iceland-golf-idUSBRE95H0KA20130618|title=Golfing in Iceland's midnight sun: lava beds, angry birds, winds|author=Paul Ingrassia|date=18 June 2013|work=Reuters|accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref> It features a [[moorland]] course, broad ridges, tree clusters, and rock [[outcrop]]pings.<ref name=golficeland.org>{{cite web|title=Akureyri golf course|url=http://golficeland.org/introduction/akureyri-golf-course.html|website=golficeland.org|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref> Due to its proximity to the [[Arctic Circle]], it is possible to play golf at Akureyri Golf Club at night under the [[midnight sun]] during the summer.

Akureyri Golf Club was established in 1935. It is Iceland‘s second-oldest golf club after [[Reykjavik Golf Club]].

Akureyri Golf Club established its current location at the Jadar farm in 1970. For ten years, the members played a 9-hole course which is now the front nine, designed by Magnus Gudmundsson. In 1980, the second nine holes were added.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Daley|first1=Paul|title=Golf Architecture: A Worldwide Perspective, Volume 3|date=2008|publisher=Pelican Publishing|isbn=9781589806160|page=92}}</ref> The second nine holes were developed and implemented by Magnus Gudmundsson and Gunnar Thordarson.

The Arctic Open is held at Akureyri Golf Club during the summer solstice. It was first held in 1986.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.golfdigest.com/story/golf-in-iceland|title=Golf in Iceland: Under the Midnight Sun - Golf Digest|author=Oliver Horovitz,Dom Furore|date=|work=Golf Digest|accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref> It is a four-day championship event, open to international professional and amateur golfers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arcticopen.is|title=Arctic Open - a true golfing adventure under the midnight sun|author=Arctic Open - a true golfing adventure under the midnight sun|date=|work=Arctic Open - a true golfing adventure under the midnight sun|accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref>

In 1997, four men completed the longest daytime round of golf in history by playing 306 holes at Akureyri Golf Club during the summer when it stays light through the night.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Zullo|first1=Alan|title=Astonishing But True Golf Facts|date=2001|publisher=Andrews McMeel Publishing|isbn=0-7407-1426-0|page=9}}</ref>

