{{Multiple issues|{{refimprove|date=September 2018}}{{context|date=September 2018}}}}
The '''Ijebu people''' are a subtribal [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] group, native to the south-central part of [[Yorubaland]] in southwest [[Nigeria]]. The Ijebu people speak Ijebu language, a sub-dialect of the [[Yoruba language]].
== Description == The Ijebu share boundaries on the north with Ibadan, on the west with the [[Egba people|Egba]] and on the east with the [[Ilaje]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bobakeye.com/ijebu-kingdom---brief-history|title=Ijebu Kingdom - Brief History|website=bobakeye}}</ref> The Ijebus are the most populous Yoruba group<ref name="the234project.com">{{cite web|url=https://the234project.com/arts-and-culture/nigeria/the-ijebu-kingdom/|title=The Ijebu Kingdom|last=|first=|date=31 January 2017|website=|publisher=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> and were allegedly the first southwest Nigerian tribe to establish relations with the Europeans in the 14th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kwekudee-tripdownmemorylane.blogspot.com/2014/08/ijebu-people-shrewd-business-like-sub.html|title=Ijebu people: shrewd business-like sub-Yoruba ethnic group who were the first Yoruba to have contact with Europeans|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> The Ijebus, though split into various divisions (including [[Ijebu Ode]], [[Ijebu Igbo]], [[Ijebu Imushin]], [[Ijebu Ife]], [[Ijebu Ososa]] and [[Ijebu Remo]]), see themselves as united under the leadership and authority of the monarchical [[Awujale]], who is seated in Ijebu Ode.<ref name="the234project.com" /> The Ijebu people are known for their [[cassava]] flakes (popularly known as [[Garri]]), trade and productivity.
==References== <references />
