[[File:Curiosity on Mars.jpg|thumb|220px|''Curiosity's'' self-portrait shows the deck of the rover as viewed from the NavCams.]] '''Navcam''', short for '''navigational camera''', is a type of [[camera]] found on certain robotic [[rover (space exploration)|rover]]s or [[spacecraft]] used for navigation without interfering with scientific instruments.<ref name="67P">{{cite web|title=Comet 67P/C-G in Rosetta’s navigation camera|url=http://blogs.esa.int/rosetta/2014/06/25/comet-67pc-g-in-rosettas-navigation-camera/|publisher=[[ESA]]|accessdate=15 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The rover's "eyes" and other "senses"|url=http://marsrover.nasa.gov/mission/spacecraft_rover_eyes.html|work=Mars Exploration Rover Mission|publisher=[[NASA Jet Propulsion Laboratory]]|accessdate=3 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=How A Team Of Scientists Dropped A One-Ton Science Lab On Mars Completely Unscathed|newspaper=[[The Business Insider]]|date=17 December 2012}}</ref> Navcams typically take wide angle photographs that are used to plan the next moves of the vehicle<ref>{{cite news|title=More Driving And Imaging At 'Matijevic Hill'|newspaper=Space Daily|date=November 26, 2012}}</ref> or object tracking.<ref name="67P"/>
==Overview== The Mars [[Curiosity rover|''Curiosity'' rover]] has two pairs of black and white navigation cameras mounted on the mast to support ground navigation. The cameras have a 45 degree [[angle of view]] and use visible [[light]] to capture [[Stereoscopy|stereoscopic 3-D imagery]].<ref>[http://www.planetary.org/blogs/emily-lakdawalla/2012/08080751-curiosity-first-navcam-pan-3d.html First NavCam mosaic]</ref> These cameras, like those on the [[Mars Pathfinder]] missions support use of the [[ICER]] image compression format{{Citation needed|date=August 2014}}.
[[European Space Agency]] [[Rosetta (spacecraft)|''Rosetta'' spacecraft]] uses a single camera with 5 degree field of view and 12 [[Color depth|bit]] 1024x1024px resolution allowing for visual tracking on each of spacecraft approaches to the asteroids and finally the [[67P/Churyumov–Gerasimenko|comet]].<ref name="67P"/>
==See also== *[[Astrionics]] *[[Hazcam|Hazard avoidance camera (Hazcam)]] *[[Pancam|Panoramic camera (Pancam)]] *[[Optical, Spectroscopic, and Infrared Remote Imaging System|Optical, Spectroscopic, and Infrared camera OSIRIS]] *[[List of NASA cameras on spacecraft]] *[[Mars rover]]
