{{Infobox military structure |name = Rooke Battery |native_name = |partof = [[Fortifications of Gibraltar]] |location =[[Gibraltar]] |image = [[File:Rooke Battery buildings Gibraltar Flickr 1185464940 f576f3693c o.jpg|240px]] |caption = Rooke Battery buildings |map_type = Gibraltar |map_size = 300 |map_alt = |map_caption = Location in [[Gibraltar]] |type = [[Artillery Battery]] |coordinates = {{coord|36.130667|-5.347845|type:landmark_region:GI|display=inline}} |code = |built = |builder = |materials = |height = |used = |demolished = |condition = |ownership = [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] |open_to_public = |controlledby = |garrison = |current_commander = |commanders = |occupants = |battles = |events = |image2 = |caption2 = }} '''Rooke Battery''' is a now derelict [[artillery battery]] on the west side of the [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] of [[Gibraltar]].
==Description== The derelict battery can now be found on the [[Footpaths of Gibraltar#Royal Anglian Way|Royal Anglian Way]] which is named after the 2nd Battalion of the Royal Anglian Regiment, who refurbished it in August 1969. The path leads up the west side to the top of the Rock passing by this battery and [[Hayne's Cave Battery]].<ref name=dg/> [[File:Royal Anglian Way.gif|thumb|left|Location of the battery]] The battery has a plaque labelled "1906" and it is named after Sir [[George Rooke]]<ref name="Sayer1865">{{cite book|last=Sayer|first=Frederick|title=The History of Gibraltar and of Its Political Relation to Events in Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q45MmghAoMgC&pg=PA118|accessdate=29 March 2013|year=1865|publisher=Chapman and Hall|page=118}}</ref> who commanded the British Fleet when Gibraltar came under British rule.
This battery's in 1907 had a [[BL 9.2 inch gun Mk IX–X]] on a Mk. V mounting which was protected against severe damage because it had an underground magazine and shelter. The popular 9.2-inch guns were also installed high on the rock at [[Spur Battery]], [[Breakneck Battery]] and similar locations. The gun is known to have still been here in 1928.<ref name=dg/>
Visitors can see the remains of the searchlight which was used during [[World War II]] when the battery was also a Fire Command headquarters which could direct the fire of other batteries.<ref name=dg>{{cite web|last=Crone|first=Jim|title=Royal Anglian Way|url=http://www.discovergibraltar.com/pages/mainlogo/mainfrm.htm|publisher=DiscoverGibraltar.com|accessdate=30 March 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130905140025/http://www.discovergibraltar.com/pages/mainlogo/mainfrm.htm|archivedate=5 September 2013|df=}}</ref>
