The '''Tielt Formation''' ({{lang-nl|Formatie van Tielt}}; {{lang-fr|Formation de Tielt}}; abbreviation: Tt; named after the town of [[Tielt]] in [[West-Flanders]]) is a [[formation (stratigraphy)|geologic formation]] in the [[Subsurface (geology)|subsurface]] of [[Belgium]]. The formation [[outcrop|crops out]] in the north of [[Hainaut (province)|Hainaut]], in the southern and central parts of West- and [[East-Flanders]] and in [[Walloon Brabant|Walloon]] and [[Flemish Brabant]]. It consists of [[marine (ocean)|marine]] very fine [[sand]] and [[silt]], deposited in the shallow sea that covered Belgium during the middle and late [[Ypresian]] [[age (geology)|age]] (early [[Eocene]], about 50 million years ago).

The Tielt Formation is 50 metres thick at most. It is subdivided into three [[member (stratigraphy)|members]]: the [[Kortemark Member]], the [[Egemkapel Member]] and the [[Egem Member]] ([[glauconite|glauconiferous]] fine sand). The formation lies stratigraphically on top of the [[Kortrijk Formation]] (early Ypresian sandy clay and silt). In the northwestern part of Belgium, the [[Gentbrugge Formation]] (late Ypresian marine clay and silt) covers the Tielt Formation. If the Gentbrugge Formation is absent, the younger [[Brussel Formation]] ([[Lutetian]] calcareous sand) is directly found on top of the Tielt Formation.

